          alt="A view of the Buildbotics Web interface")
    p.
      Make your CNC incredibly easy to use with the Buildbotics controller's
      intuitive built-in software.

    p
      a(href="https://demo.buildbotics.com/", target="_blank")
        | Click here to try the demo.

    p.
      Upload your GCode and press the play button to run a simulation of the
      real Buildbotics CNC controller.

    p See what it's like to configure motor, tool and limit switch settings.
    .clear

  include ./mailinglist.pug

  section
    h2 Compatible with most CAM software
    .cam-logos
      img(src="images/cam/fusion360.png", alt="Fusion360 logo")
      img(src="images/cam/mastercam.png", alt="MasterCAM logo")
      img(src="images/cam/vcarve.png", alt="VCarve logo")
      img(src="images/cam/bobcad.png", alt="BobCAD logo")

    p.
      The Buildbotics CNC controller accepts GCode from CAM software like
      Fusion 360, Mastercam, VCarve, BobCAD, MeshCAM, CamBam, and many others.
      Test your GCode for Buildbotics compatibility for free with
      #[a(href="https://camotics.org/") CAMotics].
    .clear

  section
    h2 Reliable Electronics
    .img-right: img(src="images/electrical_warning.png",
      alt="Electrical warning sign")
    p.
      We know you want your CNC to just work when you need it to.  Yet, many
      cheap CNC controllers were designed with little or no attention
      to electrical safety. The Buildbotics controller is protected from:

    ul
      li Over-current
      li Thermal overload
      li Under voltage
      li Reverse voltage
      li Short-circuit
      li Voltage spikes caused by motor stalls
    .clear

  section
    h2 Stay Cool without a Fan
    .img-left: img(src="images/cool_without_fan.png",
      alt="A cool thermometer and a crossed out fan")

    p.
      The Buildbotics controller protects against thermal overload.
      Through careful selection of high-quality electronic components, the
      Buildbotics controller stays cool, without a fan, even while driving 6A
      motor loads. Going fan-less not only eliminates noise but also avoids
      sucking in dust and debris.
    .clear

  section
    h2 Dedicated Computer #[b not] Required
    .img-left: img(src="images/no_mach3_or_linuxcnc.png",
      alt="Mach3 and LinuxCNC both crossed out")

    p.
      A finely tuned PC running Mach or LinuxCNC is #[b not] needed.  You can
      access the Buildbotics controller's built-in software from any of your
      devices and be sure that your CNC will run smoothly and uninterrupted.

    p.
      You can even try out your GCodes online with our
      #[a(href="//demo.buildbotics.com/", target="_blank") free demo software].
    .clear

  section
    h2 Fast, Smooth & Accurate Stepping
    .img-left: img(src="images/stepdir.png", alt="Step and direction signals")

    p.
      Get maximum performance and accuracy from your CNC. The Buildbotics
      controller achieves smooth step rates up to #[i 250,000 per second]
      allowing you to use up to 256 microstepping at high speeds.
    .clear

  section
    h2 Wired or WiFi Networking
    p.
      The Buildbotics controller offers a modern Web interface accessible from
      a browser over your local network or WiFi.  A whole network of
      Buildbotics controllers can be managed from a single computer.
    img(src="images/buildbotics_network.png",
      alt="Many Buildbotics CNC devices connected by a network")
    .clear

  section
    h2 Free Simulation Software
    p.
      All the software you need to run GCode on your CNC machine is built
      in to the Buildbotics controller but you can also use our free
      simulation software to test your GCode before you run it.

    p.
      The #[a(href="//camotics.org/", target="_blank") CAMotics] CNC
      simulator computes 3D cut previews from GCode.  CAMotics can also send
      GCode directly to the Buildbotics controller over the network and track
      the machine position while it runs.

    a(href="//camotics.org", target="_blank")
      video(autoplay="", loop="", width="600")
        source(src="video/camotics.mp4", type="video/mp4")
    .clear

  include ./buy.pug

  section
    h2 Tool Control
    img(src="images/spindles.png",
      alt="A DC CNC spindle next to a VFD CNC spindle")
    p.
      Three different options for controlling external tools, such as spindles:

    ul
      li
        a(href="/connecting-a-pwm-spindle-to-the-buildbotics-controller/")
          | Digital PWM control
      li
        a(href="/how-to-use-a-vfd-spindle-driver/") Two wire RS485 VFD control
      li
        a(href="/io-breakout/") 0-10v analog control

    .clear

  section
    h2 Drive External Loads
    .img-right: img(src="images/load_switch.png", width="400",
      alt="Buildbotics CNC controller controlling a compressor with an SSR")
    p.
      Digital outputs can switch external drivers to control
      heated beds for 3D printers, extruders, vacuum tables or whatever else
      you can think of.  Switch them on and off from your GCode programs.

    p.
      For AC loads, an inexpensive
      #[a(href="//amazon.com/s/?field-keywords=solid+state+relay") SSR]
      switch can be used.  External relays can be used for DC loads.
    .clear

  section
    h2 Aluminum Enclosure
    img(src="images/enclosure.png",
      alt="Buildbotics CNC controller aluminum enclosure")
    .img-right: img(src="images/buildbotics_enclosure_base.png",
      alt="Diagram of Buildbotics CNC controller enclosure footprint")
    p.
      By carefully considering heat throughout the design process the
      Buildbotics controller dissipates heat through its fan-less aluminum
      enclosure without sucking in metal or wood shavings.

    p.
      Four screw holes allow the enclosure to be easily mounted on or near
      the machine.
    .clear

  section
    h2 RaspberryPi Inside
    .img-right: img(src="images/raspberrypi3.png",
      alt="RaspberryPi CNC controller")
    p.
      The built-in Raspberry Pi running Linux provides massive potential for
      building your next big idea.  Install additional software on the Pi or
      use Python code to build new features.
    .clear

  section
    h2 Tested
    p.
      The Buildbotics controller has been successfully tested in many CNC builds
      both by us and our customers.

    img(src="images/cncs_we_built.png", alt="Six of the CNCs we've built")
    - var youtube_ch = "//youtube.com/channel/UC_onc2im9IrG1RxJ3CZnArw"
    p.
      We filmed the construction of a Taig CNC mill, an OX CNC router, a K40
      LASER upgrade and a Dyna Myte 2400 retrofit. Check out the videos on our
      #[a(href=youtube_ch, target="_blank") Youtube channel].
    p.
      Check out some of machines we've build with the Buildbotics CNC
      controller.

    ul
      li: a(href="taig") The Taig CNC Mill
      li: a(href="ox") The OX CNC Router
      li: a(href="6040") The 6040 CNC Router
      li: a(href="dynamyte_2400") The Dyna Myte 2400 CNC Mill
      li: a(href="k40-laser-cutter") The K40 LASER Cutter
      li: a(href="dougs-cnc") Doug's custom CNC router
    .clear

  section
    h2 Source Code, Schematics & PCB layout
    img(src="images/dev.png",
      alt="Schematics, PCB layout and the main circuit board")
    p.
      Welcome, software and hardware developers.  We’ve already
      implemented a lot of cool features but we have not even scratched the
      surface of what this controller could do. That is why we’ve made
      #[b everything 100%]
      #[a(href="https://opensource.org/osd-annotated") Open-Source].

    p Here’s what you can find on GitHub:
    ul
      li
        a(href="https://github.com/buildbotics/bbctrl-firmware")
          | Firmware source code
        | .
      li
        a(href="https://github.com/buildbotics/bbctrl-pcb")
          | Hardware schematics and PCB layout
        | .
      li
        a(href="https://github.com/buildbotics/bbctrl-enclosure")
          | Enclosure designs
        | .
    .clear

